elderly adult","It begins to involute during adolescence","It weighs 30-40 grams in the elderly adult","It is located in the posterior mediastinum","It maintains constant size throughout life"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe thymus is a primary lymphoid organ located in the anterior superior mediastinum. \u003Cstrong\u003EThe thymus\u003C/strong\u003E undergoes significant changes throughout life, but does not remain largest in \u003Cstrong\u003Ethe elderly adult\u003C/strong\u003E. Instead, it grows during childhood and reaches peak size during puberty, after which \u003Cstrong\u003Eit begins to involute\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter involution, the thymus becomes progressively smaller, not \u003Cstrong\u003E30-40 grams\u003C/strong\u003E, and is largely replaced by fatty tissue. The thymus is always located in the anterior superior mediastinum, not \u003Cstrong\u003Ein the posterior mediastinum\u003C/strong\u003E. The organ definitely does not \u003Cstrong\u003Emaintain constant size throughout life\u003C/strong\u003E - this is one of its key characteristics.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The thymus reaches its maximum size during puberty (40-50g) and undergoes age-related involution thereafter","The thymus is located in the anterior superior mediastinum","Thymic involution involves replacement of functional tissue with adipose tissue"],"references":["Gordon J, Manley NR. Mechanisms of thymus organogenesis and morphogenesis. Development. 2011 Sep;138(18):3865-78. doi: 10.1242/dev.059998. PMID: 21862553; PMCID: PMC3160085.","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd.","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":